---
/**
 * Docker Run to Compose — the primary SEO surface for the bidirectional
 * converter. Paste a `docker run …` command and get the equivalent
 * docker-compose service YAML, or paste a Compose service and rebuild the
 * `docker run` line. 100% client-side — no server, no upload, no signup.
 *
 * Mirrors the canonical tool-page structure (ToolHero → playground → why →
 * pipeline → reference → dark next-step band → FAQ + JSON-LD → cross-links).
 * The interactive island (DockerRunToComposePlayground) self-mounts; JSON-LD
 * (SoftwareApplication + FAQPage) is assembled here and handed to Shell.
 */
import Shell from '../components/Shell.astro';
import DockerRunToComposePlayground from '../components/DockerRunToComposePlayground.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import ToolHero from '../components/ToolHero.astro';
import ToolGapVisual from '../components/ToolGapVisual.astro';
import ToolPipeline from '../components/ToolPipeline.astro';
import FaqList from '../components/FaqList.astro';
import ToolCrossLinks from '../components/ToolCrossLinks.astro';
import { site, navLinks } from '../data/site';
import { getTool } from '../data/tools';
import { softwareAppLd, faqPageLd } from '../lib/jsonld';

const tool = getTool('docker-run-to-compose');

const pagePath = '/docker-run-to-compose/';
const pageUrl = `${site.url}${pagePath}`;

// ── External references (canonical Docker docs) ──────────────────────────────
const dockerRunRef = 'https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/run/';
const composeFileRef = 'https://docs.docker.com/reference/compose-file/services/';
const composeUpRef = 'https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/up/';

// ── FAQ content — single source for both the rendered section and FAQPage LD ─
const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How do I convert a docker run command to docker-compose.yml?',
    a: 'Paste the full docker run command into this docker run to compose converter with the mode set to run → compose, then press Convert. It strips the leading docker run, classifies each flag onto a service object, treats the first non-flag token as the image and the rest as the command, and prints a ready-to-use docker-compose.yml services: block — no install, no Docker daemon, and nothing pushed anywhere. The whole convert docker run to docker-compose.yml flow happens in the browser.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I convert docker-compose back to a docker run command?',
    a: 'Yes — this is a bidirectional docker run / docker compose converter. Switch the mode toggle to compose → run, paste a service definition (or a full Compose file — the first service is used), and it reconstructs an equivalent docker run command, including ports, volumes, environment, networks, capabilities, resource limits and a healthcheck. This docker compose to docker run command converter reports keys with no docker run equivalent — depends_on, build, deploy, profiles — as warnings rather than translating them.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do docker run flags map to docker-compose fields?',
    a: 'The common docker run flags map cleanly: -p/--publish → ports, -v/--volume and --mount → volumes, -e/--env → environment, --env-file → env_file, --name → container_name, --restart → restart, --network/--net → networks (or network_mode for host/none), -w/--workdir → working_dir, -u/--user → user, --entrypoint → entrypoint, --hostname → hostname, --add-host → extra_hosts, --cap-add/--cap-drop → cap_add/cap_drop, --privileged → privileged, -m/--memory → mem_limit, --cpus → cpus, -l/--label → labels, and the --health-* flags → a healthcheck block. -i and -t map to stdin_open and tty.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How does docker run -p map to ports in docker compose?',
    a: 'Each -p / --publish flag becomes an entry under the ports: list in the Compose service, written as a quoted "HOST:CONTAINER" string — so docker run -p 8080:80 turns into a ports entry of "8080:80". The converter quotes the value because YAML would otherwise read a bare 8080:80 as a sexagesimal number, which is exactly the kind of subtle bug that hand-conversion of docker run -p -v -e to compose tends to introduce.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I convert docker run -v volumes to a compose file?',
    a: 'Every -v / --volume (and --mount) flag is collected into the volumes: list on the service, keeping the short source:target[:ro] form, so docker run -v /data:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro becomes a volumes entry of /data:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro. Named volumes and bind mounts are preserved as written; the tool does not invent a top-level volumes: section you did not ask for.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How are docker run -e environment variables written in docker-compose?',
    a: 'Each -e / --env flag becomes a KEY=value entry under environment: in the service, and any --env-file is mapped to env_file:. Because the conversion is docker run to compose yaml with no upload, you can safely paste commands whose -e flags carry secret-bearing values or internal hostnames — they are tokenised in your browser and never sent anywhere.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What does --restart become in a docker-compose service?',
    a: 'The docker run restart policy maps straight to the restart: key in Compose: --restart no, --restart always, --restart on-failure[:max] and --restart unless-stopped are carried across unchanged. So docker run --restart unless-stopped becomes restart: unless-stopped in the generated service.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is this docker run to compose converter free and does it work offline?',
    a: 'Yes. It is a free docker run to compose converter that runs 100% client-side, so it works as a docker run to compose converter that runs in the browser — there is no server, no account and no signup, and once the page has loaded it keeps working with no network. That also makes it a docker run to docker compose converter with no install: nothing is uploaded and nothing is installed on your machine.',
  },
];

// ── JSON-LD: SoftwareApplication + FAQPage (shared builders) ─────────────────
const softwareApp = softwareAppLd({
  name: 'Docker Run to Compose Converter',
  description:
    'Free bidirectional Docker Run ↔ Compose converter. Paste a docker run command to get the equivalent docker-compose service YAML, or convert a Compose service back to a docker run command. 100% in-browser, no install, no signup.',
  url: pageUrl,
  subCategory: 'Docker Tooling',
  featureList: [
    'Convert any docker run command to a docker-compose.yml service',
    'Reverse direction: rebuild the docker run line from a Compose service',
    'Maps -p ports, -v volumes, -e env, --restart, --network and more',
    'Runs 100% client-side — nothing is uploaded and no signup needed',
    'Clear warnings for flags that need manual review',
    'One-click copy of the generated YAML or command',
  ],
  keywords: tool?.keywords.join(', '),
});

const faqPage = faqPageLd(faqs);

// ── HOW IT WORKS pipeline ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const pipeline = [
  {
    title: 'Tokenise the command.',
    body: 'A POSIX-aware tokeniser splits the line, honouring single and double quotes and backslash-newline continuations, so quoted values and multi-line pastes stay intact.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Strip the prefix.',
    body: 'A leading docker run or docker container run is removed, and bundled short flags like -it or -itp are expanded into their individual flags.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Classify each flag.',
    body: 'Every flag is mapped onto a service object — ports, volumes, environment, networks, capabilities, limits, labels and healthcheck — and the first positional becomes the image, the rest the command.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Emit deterministic YAML.',
    body: 'A small hand-rolled writer prints a stable, diff-friendly services: block keyed by the container name (or app), quoting only the scalars that YAML requires.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Or reverse it.',
    body: 'In compose → run mode the same model is rebuilt from parsed Compose YAML into a docker run command, with Compose-only keys surfaced as warnings.',
  },
];

// ── MAPPING REFERENCE — flag ↔ Compose key, with a worked example ─────────────
const mappings = [
  { flag: '-p / --publish', key: 'ports', note: 'Quoted, e.g. "8080:80".' },
  { flag: '-v / --volume, --mount', key: 'volumes', note: 'Short source:target[:ro] form.' },
  { flag: '-e / --env', key: 'environment', note: 'A KEY=value list.' },
  { flag: '--env-file', key: 'env_file', note: 'One or more files.' },
  { flag: '--name', key: 'container_name', note: 'Also the service key.' },
  { flag: '--restart', key: 'restart', note: 'no / always / unless-stopped …' },
  { flag: '--network / --net', key: 'networks', note: 'host / none → network_mode.' },
  { flag: '-w / --workdir', key: 'working_dir', note: '' },
  { flag: '-u / --user', key: 'user', note: '' },
  { flag: '--entrypoint', key: 'entrypoint', note: '' },
  { flag: '--hostname', key: 'hostname', note: '' },
  { flag: '--add-host', key: 'extra_hosts', note: '' },
  { flag: '--cap-add / --cap-drop', key: 'cap_add / cap_drop', note: '' },
  { flag: '--privileged', key: 'privileged', note: '' },
  { flag: '-m / --memory', key: 'mem_limit', note: '' },
  { flag: '--cpus', key: 'cpus', note: '' },
  { flag: '-l / --label', key: 'labels', note: '' },
  { flag: '--health-*', key: 'healthcheck', note: 'cmd / interval / timeout / retries.' },
  { flag: '-i / -t', key: 'stdin_open / tty', note: '' },
  { flag: '--rm, -d / --detach', key: '— (warning)', note: 'No Compose equivalent.' },
];

const beforeCmd =
  'docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name web \\\n  -v /data:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro \\\n  --restart unless-stopped nginx:alpine';
const afterYaml = `services:
  web:
    image: nginx:alpine
    container_name: web
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
    volumes:
      - /data:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro
    restart: unless-stopped`;
---

<Shell
  title="Docker Run to Docker Compose Converter | OpsCanopy"
  description="Free docker run to docker compose converter. Paste a docker run command, get a docker-compose.yml service, and convert back. 100% in-browser, no signup."
  canonical="/docker-run-to-compose"
  jsonLd={[softwareApp, faqPage]}
>
  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       1) HERO
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolHero
    slug="docker-run-to-compose"
    eyebrow="Docker Run to Compose · Docker"
    badges={[
      { label: 'Runs in your browser', variant: 'live' },
      { label: 'No signup', variant: 'neutral' },
      { label: 'Bidirectional', variant: 'neutral' },
    ]}
  >
    <Fragment slot="headline">
      The <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker run</span> to Docker Compose converter — and back.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      A free docker run to docker compose converter: paste a
      <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker run</span> command and get the equivalent
      <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker-compose.yml</span> service, or paste a
      Compose service to rebuild the command line. Instant, in your browser. No install, no signup.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolHero>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       2) THE PLAYGROUND
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="playground" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-canvas-soft pb-20 pt-8 sm:pb-24">
    <div class="container-page">
      <h2 class="sr-only">Docker Run to Compose converter playground</h2>
      <DockerRunToComposePlayground />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       3) WHY IT EXISTS — the gap
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="why" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[0.9fr_1.1fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The Gap</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-ink">
            One container, two shapes.
          </h2>
          <ToolGapVisual />
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            A <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker run</span> command is great for a
            quick start, but the moment you want it reproducible — in version control, reviewed in a PR,
            started with one command — you need to take that docker run command to compose form in a
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker-compose.yml</span>. Translating a
            wall of <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">-p</span>,
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">-v</span> and
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">-e</span> flags by hand is tedious and
            error-prone: it is easy to drop a flag, mis-nest a list, or quote a port wrong.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            This docker run to docker-compose generator does the mechanical part for you,
            <strong class="font-medium text-ink">both ways</strong>. It tokenises the command exactly
            like a shell would — respecting quotes, bundled short flags, and line continuations — maps
            each flag onto the matching Compose key, and emits deterministic YAML to turn docker run
            into a docker-compose service. Going the other direction it handles docker compose to
            docker run too: it rebuilds a runnable command from a service and tells you about the keys
            (<span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">depends_on</span>,
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">build</span>,
            <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">deploy</span>) that simply have no command
            equivalent.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            Because it is a docker run to compose online tool, you can convert a docker run command to
            docker compose online free with nothing to download — no daemon, no account, no waiting on
            a build.
          </p>
          <p class="body-md text-pretty text-body">
            Everything runs in your browser, so you can convert commands that name private registries
            or secret-bearing environment variables without anything leaving the tab. See the
            <a class="link-inline" href={dockerRunRef} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
              ><span translate="no">docker run</span> reference</a
            > and the
            <a class="link-inline" href={composeFileRef} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
              >Compose services reference</a
            >.
          </p>
          <p class="body-sm text-mute">
            See the full <a class="link-inline" href="#reference">flag-to-key mapping</a>, or try the
            <a class="link-inline" href="#playground">live playground</a> above.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       4) HOW IT WORKS — numbered pipeline
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolPipeline
    id="how-it-works"
    eyebrow="The Pipeline"
    heading="How to convert docker run flags to docker compose."
    lead="Five deterministic steps turn docker run into a docker-compose service end-to-end on every conversion — all inside your browser tab, every time."
    steps={pipeline}
  />

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       5) REFERENCE — flag ↔ key mapping + a worked example
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="reference" class="scroll-mt-24 border-t border-hairline bg-canvas">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center">
        <p class="eyebrow">Reference</p>
        <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-ink">Every flag, mapped.</h2>
        <p class="body-md mx-auto mt-3 max-w-xl text-pretty text-body">
          The <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker run</span> flags the converter
          recognises and the <span class="code-mono text-ink" translate="no">docker-compose</span>
          keys they map to. Anything unrecognised is reported as a note instead of being silently dropped.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mx-auto mt-10 grid max-w-5xl items-start gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="card-soft overflow-hidden">
          <table class="drc-table w-full text-left">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th class="eyebrow px-4 py-3"><span translate="no">docker run</span> flag</th>
                <th class="eyebrow px-4 py-3">Compose key</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {
                mappings.map((m) => (
                  <tr class="border-t border-hairline align-top">
                    <td class="code-mono px-4 py-2.5 text-ink" translate="no">{m.flag}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5">
                      <span class="code-mono text-brand-strong" translate="no">{m.key}</span>
                      {m.note && <span class="caption mt-0.5 block text-mute">{m.note}</span>}
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                ))
              }
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-5">
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow mb-2">Input</p>
            <CodeBlock lang="bash" filename="docker run" code={beforeCmd} />
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow mb-2 !text-success">Output</p>
            <CodeBlock lang="yaml" filename="docker-compose.yml" code={afterYaml} />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="caption mx-auto mt-10 max-w-3xl text-center text-pretty text-mute">
        After converting, start the service with
        <a class="link-inline" href={composeUpRef} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
          ><span class="code-mono" translate="no">docker compose up -d</span></a
        > — the Compose equivalent of the original <span class="code-mono" translate="no">-d</span> flag.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       6) NEXT STEP — dark band, CTAs to related tools
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section id="next" class="scroll-mt-24 bg-inverse text-inverse-fg">
    <div class="container-page py-16 sm:py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto grid max-w-5xl items-center gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr] lg:gap-16">
        <div class="min-w-0">
          <p class="eyebrow !text-cyan">Next Step</p>
          <h2 class="display-lg mt-3 text-balance text-inverse-fg">
            Got the service? Validate the pipeline and size the pods.
          </h2>
          <p class="body-md mt-4 text-pretty text-white/70">
            A Compose service rarely ships alone. Lint the
            <span translate="no">CI</span> that builds and pushes the image with the
            <span translate="no">GitLab CI Validator</span>, and when you move the container to
            Kubernetes, turn its memory and CPU limits into safe
            <span translate="no">requests/limits</span> with the
            <span translate="no">Kubernetes Resource Calculator</span> — both entirely in your browser.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-7 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
            <Button href="/gitlab-ci-validator/" variant="secondary">Open the GitLab CI Validator</Button>
            <Button href="/kubernetes-resource-calculator/" variant="secondary"
              >Open the Resource Calculator</Button
            >
          </div>
        </div>
        <CodeBlock
          lang="bash"
          filename="next.sh"
          code={`# build, push, deploy
docker build -t app .
docker compose up -d        # ← from this converter
kubectl apply -f deploy.yml # ← size it first`}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       7) FAQ
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <FaqList faqs={faqs} />

  <div class="container-page py-4">
    <p class="body-sm text-mute">New to this? Read our guide on <a href="/learn/guides/docker-for-devops/" class="link-inline">Docker for DevOps</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       Cross-links + footer disclaimer
       ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <ToolCrossLinks slug="docker-run-to-compose">
    <Fragment slot="lead">
      The <span translate="no">Docker</span> Run to Compose converter is one tool in
      <span translate="no">{site.name}</span> — a growing canopy of browser-based validators,
      converters and testers that never touch a server.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="links">
      Related tools: the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/gitlab-ci-validator/"><span translate="no">GitLab CI</span> validator</a
      > and the
      <a class="link-inline" href="/kubernetes-resource-calculator/"
        ><span translate="no">Kubernetes</span> resource calculator</a
      >. Browse the full
      <a class="link-inline" href={navLinks[0].href}>tools directory</a>.
    </Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="disclaimer">
      Not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by <span translate="no">Docker, Inc.</span>
      <span translate="no">Docker</span>, <span translate="no">docker run</span> and
      <span translate="no">Docker Compose</span> are trademarks of
      <span translate="no">Docker, Inc.</span>, used here only descriptively to identify the command
      and file formats this tool converts between.
    </Fragment>
  </ToolCrossLinks>
</Shell>

<style>
  @reference "../styles/global.css";

  .drc-table th {
    font-weight: inherit;
  }
  .drc-table td {
    font-size: 13px;
    line-height: 18px;
  }
</style>
